There may be others but I saw this today...

```
type RBDVolumeSource struct {
    // Required: CephMonitors is a collection of Ceph monitors
    CephMonitors []string `json:"monitors"`
    // Required: RBDImage is the rados image name
    RBDImage string `json:"image"`
    // Required: Filesystem type to mount.
    // Must be a filesystem type supported by the host operating system.
    // Ex. "ext4", "xfs", "ntfs"
    // TODO: how do we prevent errors in the filesystem from compromising the machine
    FSType string `json:"fsType,omitempty"`
    // Optional: RadosPool is the rados pool name,default is rbd
    RBDPool string `json:"pool"`
    // Optional: RBDUser is the rados user name, default is admin
    RadosUser string `json:"user"`
```

I think that, in general we want field names and JSON tags to match unless there's a good reason for them not to.  I see no good reason here.  Probably field names should change, leaving tags (the API) untouched.

@markturansky @rootfs

When we create GCE load-balancers we have to use an opaque name to fit.  We should populate the description field with enough information to help humans figure out what it is for and to be machine usable.

Maybe a JSON-formatted set of Key-Value pairs or something, including the k8s cluster name, namespace, and service name (at minimum)

@arob for any clues on why we don't do this

code in `cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/plugins.go`:

```
    nfsConfig := volume.VolumeConfig{
        RecyclerMinimumTimeout:   int(config.PersistentVolumeRecyclerConfiguration.MinimumTimeoutNFS),
        RecyclerTimeoutIncrement: int(config.PersistentVolumeRecyclerConfiguration.IncrementTimeoutNFS),
        RecyclerPodTemplate:      volume.NewPersistentVolumeRecyclerPodTemplate(),
    }
```

Volume plugins should be opaque.  We need to find a way for params like this to come through without open-coding lists of parameters per volume plugin type.  This will take some thinking, and it will have to be compatible for a while.

@saad-ali @jsafrane @matchstick

xref: https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/47221#issuecomment-307388031

Specifically, DNS uses the same port number in TCP and UDP.  This is valid when the object is created, but any PATCH operation related to Service ports will merge those together, which is wrong.

