comment_text:
This is not a public API (at least not outside of k/k) so we can always change it in the event we really do need an interface.  But it seems like a "dumb data object" is appropriate.  Even with a function pointer.

I like `Descriptor` or `Handle` because this object is the beginning of a controller.  It's not running yet.  It holds metadata, but we have too many `*Meta` things.

Alternately, you could make this all part of `controller.Interface` and document that lifecycle as having a pre-running phase.  That spreads out the metadata more and puts it near the controller implementation, which I am not sure is right.  This feels like an "inode vs. file" thing - many inodes (names and aliases) can refer to the same file (descriptor).  That said, the only method in `controller.Interface` is `Name()` and it seems like many of these `start` functions return `nil` (e.g. `startServiceController`) for the controller.Interface anyway!!  That should be a cleanup of its own.

`newEndpointsControllerDescriptor` is long but not terrible.  It says what it means.  `newEndpointsControllerDesc` is a bit shorter and not much less readable.  Either one satisfies your criteria.  

So I would say either something like

```
func newFooControllerDescriptor() ControllerDescriptor {
    return ControllerDescriptor{
        Name: "foo",
        Aliases: []string{"foo-ctrl"},
        Run: startFooController,
    }
}

func startFooController() error {
    // lots of stuff
}
```

or else bake this into `controller.Interface` like:

```
type Interface interface {
    Name() string
    Aliases() []string
    Run(ctrlCtxControllerContext ) error
}
````

and then just call `NewFooController() controller.Interface`, check gates, then call the Run() method on it.

