@alexzielenski @apelisse 

I started applying the newly updated +default and I hit a case of a field which is `int32` (Go's zero-value is 0) and whose documented default value is 0.  I thought it was valuable to say `+default=0` in the comment-tags (which is ~ an IDL now) so we can eventually generate docs from it.

When I did that, the code-generator gave me:

```
+       if in.Spec.MinReadySeconds == 0 {
+               in.Spec.MinReadySeconds = 0
+       }
```

Which is obviously nonsense.  We should recognize that the documented default is the Go zero value and not emit anything (or just emit a comment like `// MinReadySeconds default is it's zero-value.`

Now, this field (being optional) should probably be a pointer, but we have lots of cases where we rely on the zero-value.

@alexzielenski @apelisse 

It's well understood that PodSpec is embedded in all sorts of types, so any new defaults in there change all those other types.  Usually we don't want that, and so the hand-coded defaulting has ` SetDefaults_PodSpec()` (which captures the existing ones) and `SetDefaults_Pod()` (which only triggers on actual Pod, which is where most new defaults should go).

There's no way to denote this with `+default`.  Maybe we don't want to because it is so specific to this case, but I wanted to file it to think about.

Example: Service has code like:

```
if svc.Spec.Type == "" { 
    svc.Spec.Type = defaultType
}

// ... later ...

if svc.Spec.Type == "ClusterIP" {
    if svc.Spec.InternalTrafficPolicy == "" {
        svc.Spec.InternalTrafficPolicy = defaultITP
    }
}
```

The generated defaulting code looks like:

```
func SetObjectDefaults_Service(...) {
    // Call hand-written code
    SetDefaults_Service(...)
    // Call generated code
}
```

I converted the simple default for Type to `+default` but since we don't have conditional `+default`, I left the ITP logic.  The problem is that the hand-written ITP logic needs the generated code to run first.  We could call the hand-written code AFTER the generated code - is that safe?

@alexzielenski @apelisse

