This is how we can use a "regular" tag to a "regular" validator function to effect optionalness.  It's a very special case which I guess we COULD handle specially, but I was not 100% convinced it's the ONLY case of this, but it is the only case SO FAR.

Basically the caller knows (via flags) that this validator is a ShortCircuit and NonError, and can handle it by not running further validation.  Look at the generated code and see things like:

```
    // field Struct.StringField    
    errs = append(errs,    
        func(fldPath *field.Path, obj, oldObj *string) (errs field.ErrorList) {    
            if e := validate.OptionalValue(opCtx, fldPath, obj, oldObj); len(e) != 0 {    
                return // do not proceed    
            }    
            errs = append(errs, validate.FixedResult(opCtx, fldPath, obj, oldObj, false, "field Struct.StringField")...)    
            return    
        }(fldPath.Child("stringField"), &obj.StringField, safe.Field(oldObj, func(oldObj *Struct) *string { return &oldObj.StringField }))...)
```

The fact that we need `OptionalValue()` and `OptionalPointer()` is some of what we were discussing earlier today, and I'm hoping we can get rid of the Slice and Map forms (hence my questions about whether it makes sense to support optional or just minItems).

